Enum EventPriority

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.lang.Enum<EventPriority>
      • io.github.kushnirvladyslav.EventPriority
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Comparable<EventPriority>

    public enum EventPriority
extends Enum<EventPriority>
    Enumeration of event priority levels used for event processing order. Higher numerical values indicate higher priority in the event queue.

    Priority levels are used by the EventManager to determine the processing order of events in the priority queue, with CRITICAL events processed first and LOW events processed last.

    Since:
    2025-06-11
    Version:
    1.0
    Author:
    Vladyslav Kushnir
    See Also:
    Event.priorityComparator(Event, Event)

    • Enum Constant Summary

      Enum Constants 
      Enum Constant and Description
      CRITICAL
      Critical priority level - events are processed first.
      HIGH
      High priority level - events are processed before medium and low priority events.
      LOW
      Lowest priority level - events are processed last.
      MEDIUM
      Medium priority level - default priority for most events.

    • Enum Constant Detail

      • LOW

        public static final EventPriority LOW
        Lowest priority level - events are processed last. Used for non-urgent background tasks and cleanup operations.

      • MEDIUM

        public static final EventPriority MEDIUM
        Medium priority level - default priority for most events. Used for regular application operations and user interactions.

      • HIGH

        public static final EventPriority HIGH
        High priority level - events are processed before medium and low priority events. Used for important operations that should be handled promptly.

      • CRITICAL

        public static final EventPriority CRITICAL
        Critical priority level - events are processed first. Used for system-critical operations, error handling, and shutdown procedures.
